postcontent: Surefire RYDER 9mm Ti SureFire introduced the Ryder Series in 2014 with the Ryder 22-A.  The concept was born of a desire to bridge the gap between the venerated and battle-proven SOCOM line and the mass market.  SureFire is finally coming around to the idea that shooters (not just government agencies) want their product and they want it with the same level of standards that SureFire built their name on.  Enter, SureFire Ryder 9Ti. Starting with a titanium tube, front cap and rear plate that keep the overall system weight to a minimum without sacrificing anything in the way of strength.  The tube is designed around a 1.24" diameter to give you a better sight picture while retaining the benifits of a cylidrical silencer.  Baffles are stainless steel and heat treated to provide maximum durability.  The patented “pig-nose” design is unique twist to the equation.  The architecture of the baffle is designed to precisely direct the gasses of a 9mm cartridge.  From our testing, the “superior sound attenuation” is a fact rather than an unsupported claim.  Additionally, the spacers (or shields) built into each baffle act as a barrier to keep carbon build-up from making its way between baffle and outer tube.  This means that after a light day on the range or a heavy week-long course, the system will still be easily disassembled.  Lastly, indexing notches and numbers engraved on each baffle make assembly a cinch. To top everything off, a Cerakote finish (available in Black, Dark Earth and Grey) to protect your investment and match the color of your rig(s).  The Ryder 9Ti ships with a black nylon pouch, assembly/disassembly tool and – as always – the SureFire No-Hassle Guarantee. postcontent: New in box, never fired.Certainly one of the most unusual-looking guns to come out is the Mossberg 500 Chainsaw. Built in the iconic Mossberg 500 action, the Chainsaw is a pistol-grip pump-action shotgun with no stock. While guns like this are desirable for home defense, they're notoriously hard to control while firing, a problem that Mossberg has solved by attaching a wrap-around chainsaw-style hand grip to the pump. Intended to be fired from the hip, this top handle allows the user to cycle the action while simultaneously maintaining leverage above the gun to help tame muzzle flip. In addition to the chainsaw-style grip, the 500 Chainsaw has a stand-off barrel that can be used to breech doors and three rails that can mount accessories.

title: For Sale:  Kel-Tec KSG  ****FDE***
postcontent:
This is the TAN or Flat Dark Earth (FDE) Version
The KSG is our first entry into the shotgun market. The size, shape and design are similar to the currently available Kel-Tec RFB rifle, but the KSG ejects downward, instead of forward. The KSG weighs 6.9lbs and is as compact as legally possible with a 26.1″ overall length and an 18.5″ cylinder bore barrel. Even with this compact size, the internal dual tube magazines hold an impressive 6 rounds of 12 gage 3″ shells each, for a total capacity of 6 6 1 (7 per tube if using 2-3/4″ shells). The simple and reliable pump action feeds from either the left or right tube. The feed side is manually selected by a lever located behind the trigger guard. The lever can be positioned in the center detent in order to easily clear the chamber without feeding another round from either magazine. A cross bolt style safety blocks the sear, and the pump release lever is located in front of the trigger guard. The pump includes an under Picatinny rail for the mounting of a forward grip, or a light or laser. The included top Picatinny sight rail will accept many types of optics or iron sights. Forward and rear sling loops are built in, and a basic sling is included. The soft rubber butt pad helps to tame recoil.
